              <table id="EditorialReviewsPanel" class="ReviewSection" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%"><tr><td>
	
                <DIV class="ReviewHeading">Amazon.com:</DIV>
                <span id="Label1">Red Pine (a.k.a. Bill Porter) offers a new perspective on the Chinese classic Taoteching. A competent translator and interpreter of Chinese religion, he renders his work with an eye for detail and a spiritualism cultivated during years of Zen monastery living. It's odd that many read translations of Chinese classics as bare-bones texts, whereas no Chinese would tackle such obscurity in the absence of a helping hand from previous pundits. Fortunately, it is no longer necessary to rely on mystical insight in order to understand the Taoteching. Instead, we can look to the 12 or so commentators that Red Pine resurrects from Chinese history. With its clarity and scholarly range, this version of the Taoteching works as both a readable text and a valuable resource of Taoist interpretation.</span>
              
</td></tr></table>
              <table id="CustomerReviewsPanel" class="ReviewSection" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%"><tr><td>
	
                <DIV class="ReviewHeading">Customer reviews:</DIV>
                
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">An essential translation</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>0</span>
                      /
                      <span>0</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-04-27</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>    As, of late, my spiritual focus has been shifting from Buddhism to Taoism, I've found myself, of neccessity, reading and re-reading various translations of the Tao Te Ching.  I think it was after reading the Feng/English illustrated translation that I began to come to the realization that translating this text is kind of difficult and that a definitive translation of the Tao Te Ching is pretty much impossible.  Ancient Chinese strikes me as a rather thorny language, and Lao Tzu's use of it - his terse and quite lyrical poetics - only add to the difficulty.   It's no wonder there are upwards of 70 translations of the thing, of varying quality.  
<br />
<br />    But Red Pine's effort stands, I think, near the top.  For a number of reasons.  For one, he draws on multiple variants of the original text, dancing back and forth to seek the clearest words.  More importantly, he includes commentaries from numerous sources - Taoist, Confucian, Buddhist.  Given the opacity of the ancient Chinese, it's my understanding that there are few who would undertake a reading of something in the language sans commentary - including it is a *very* helpful choice.  
<br />
<br />    And I have to say I do like the the inclusion, neatly printed, of the original Chinese.  Having just finished Alan Watts's Tao: The Watercourse Way, which begins with a lengthy monologue on the virtues of an ideographic language in general and Chinese in particular, my interest in written Chinese has been piqued.  And it's quite nice to be able to go from a line of English to a line of Chinese and get a rough feel for what's going on.
<br />
<br />    Any complaints?  Personally, being something of a linguistics geek, I would have like Red Pine to add more talk of the nuts and bolts of his translation.  As it is, he confines his comment to explaining major divergences from the commonly accepted text.  I understand why he did it - a desire to keep each verse contained on two pages - but I wish he'd perhaps thrown this sort of commentary into some end notes or something.  A last complaint would be that there seem to be times when Red Pine sacrifices lyricism for clarity.  While this is a very poetic translation, there are moments of clunkiness, where beuaty takes a back seat.  Then again, 'True words aren't beautiful, beautiful words aren't true,' so there you go.
<br />
<br />    These quibbles (and they are nothing more than that) aside, this is an excellent translation.  While you should certainly not limit yourself to it in your studies, it is an essential one that I give my highest recommendation.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Indispensible</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
